{"id": "16190", "revid": "40389549", "url": "https://wowpedia.fandom.com/wiki?curid=16190", "title": "Gargoyle", "text": "Gargoyles are large, vicious &lt;a href=\"bat\"&gt;bat&lt;/a&gt;-like creatures from &lt;a href=\"Northrend\"&gt;Northrend&lt;/a&gt; who have the ability to temporarily turn to stone. Most of them serve the &lt;a href=\"Scourge\"&gt;Undead Scourge&lt;/a&gt;.\nBackground.\nThe gargoyles of Northrend are voracious flying creatures who revel in slaughter and mayhem. Although they are beasts of flesh and blood, they have rough, crystalline hides which protect them from attacks and make them look like animated stone. When in danger, they can land and quickly condense their hides into a stone-like surface to make themselves almost impervious to damage. They must remain motionless while in this stone form, but it gives them time to replenish their energies. They can use this ability to pose as statues until an enemy gets close, at which point they come to life and attack.\nGargoyles make effective scouts and can be deadly if left to rain attacks from the air, but they have an obvious weakness: most of them have to go through long periods resting in stone form to maintain the energy needed to carry their heavy bodies through the air. During this time, they are vulnerable and can be easily destroyed. While in stone form, they can be shattered into fragments. In combat, gargoyles use their claws and teeth or kill their enemies by picking them up and dropping them from tall heights. Some can spit acid or poison.\nGargoyles serve as scouts, sentries, and powerful shock troopers in the &lt;a href=\"Scourge\"&gt;Scourge&lt;/a&gt;. Scourge gargoyles are \"made animate\" and given deadly attack capabilities at &lt;a href=\"Crypt%20%28Warcraft%20III%29\"&gt;crypts&lt;/a&gt;. Smaller gargoyles called &lt;a href=\"Grotesque%20Statue\"&gt;grotesques&lt;/a&gt; are used to divert the flow of rainwater on Scourge buildings to prevent mausoleum flooding. The Scourge brought gargoyles with them from &lt;a href=\"Northrend\"&gt;Northrend&lt;/a&gt; for the &lt;a href=\"Scourge%20invasion%20of%20Quel%27Thalas\"&gt;invasion of Quel'Thalas&lt;/a&gt; during the &lt;a href=\"Third%20War\"&gt;Third War&lt;/a&gt;. The creatures wheeled above &lt;a href=\"Arthas%20Menethil\"&gt;Arthas&lt;/a&gt;' marching army like buzzards and notably intercepted the runners that &lt;a href=\"Sylvanas%20Windrunner\"&gt;Sylvanas Windrunner&lt;/a&gt; sent to &lt;a href=\"Silvermoon%20City\"&gt;Silvermoon&lt;/a&gt;. During the attack on the capital, swarms of gargoyles clashed with and eventually outnumbered the &lt;a href=\"high%20elf\"&gt;elven&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"dragonhawk%20rider\"&gt;dragonhawk rider&lt;/a&gt;s, while another flock attacked and sank three ships\u2014the \"&lt;a href=\"Morn%27danel\"&gt;Morn'danel&lt;/a&gt;\", the \"&lt;a href=\"Fellovar\"&gt;Fellovar&lt;/a&gt;\", and the \"&lt;a href=\"Varillian\"&gt;Varillian&lt;/a&gt;\"\u2014trying to evacuate elven children.\nSome gargoyles have left the Scourge and serve the &lt;a href=\"Knights%20of%20the%20Ebon%20Blade\"&gt;Knights of the Ebon Blade&lt;/a&gt;. Some &lt;a href=\"death%20knight\"&gt;death knight&lt;/a&gt;s can summon them using special collars. &lt;a href=\"Forsaken\"&gt;Forsaken&lt;/a&gt; gargoyles participated in the &lt;a href=\"Battle%20for%20Darkshore\"&gt;Battle for Darkshore&lt;/a&gt;.\nAs a companion pet.\n&lt;a href=\"Grotesque%20Statue\"&gt;Grotesque Statue&lt;/a&gt; has a chance to drop from &lt;a href=\"Azgalor%20%28tactics%29\"&gt;Azgalor&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Hyjal%20Summit%20%28Caverns%20of%20Time%29\"&gt;Hyjal Summit&lt;/a&gt;.\nIn the RPG.\nGargoyles are not undead creatures in the &lt;a href=\"Warcraft%20RPG\"&gt;Warcraft RPG&lt;/a&gt;, unlike in \"Warcraft III\" and \"World of Warcraft\". &lt;a href=\"Manual%20of%20Monsters/Appendix%20Three\"&gt;Appendix Three&lt;/a&gt; of \"&lt;a href=\"Manual%20of%20Monsters\"&gt;Manual of Monsters&lt;/a&gt;\" describes a different type of &lt;a href=\"Manual%20of%20Monsters/Appendix%20Three%23Gargoyle\"&gt;gargoyle&lt;/a&gt; which is described as formed of stone and earth and a proto-golem, however, the validity of the source is disputed. Many kinds of gargoyles can be found around &lt;a href=\"Azeroth\"&gt;Azeroth&lt;/a&gt;, some of the more common types include the subspecies of gargoyle represented by various groups of mobs, as well as the &lt;a href=\"dire%20gargoyle\"&gt;dire gargoyle&lt;/a&gt; (subspecies, possibly to differentiate from the normal gargoyle in Appendix Three). In \"&lt;a href=\"Manual%20of%20Monsters\"&gt;Manual of Monsters&lt;/a&gt;\" &lt;a href=\"Manual%20of%20Monsters/Appendix%20Three\"&gt;Appendix Three&lt;/a&gt;, there are other subspecies of gargoyles: &lt;a href=\"Manual%20of%20Monsters/Appendix%20Three%23Gargoyles%2C%20all%20-%20Four-Armed%20Gargoyle%2C%20Green%20Gargoyle%2C%20Margoyle\"&gt;Four-Armed Gargoyle, Green Gargoyle, and Margoyle&lt;/a&gt;, however, the validity of the source is disputed.\nLanguage: &lt;a href=\"Low%20Common\"&gt;Low Common&lt;/a&gt;.\nSpeculation.\nIt is not known what relation, if any, the gargoyles of &lt;a href=\"Azeroth\"&gt;Azeroth&lt;/a&gt; have to the &lt;a href=\"stoneborn\"&gt;stoneborn&lt;/a&gt; gargoyles of &lt;a href=\"Revendreth\"&gt;Revendreth&lt;/a&gt;. They may be a result of the &lt;a href=\"Lich%20King\"&gt;Lich King&lt;/a&gt; seeing the stoneborn through the &lt;a href=\"Helm%20of%20Domination\"&gt;Helm of Domination&lt;/a&gt; and attempting to copy them, though the gargoyles' description in the implies that gargoyles are native creatures of Northrend that were simply recruited by the Scourge. They may be stoneborn themselves who escaped or were brought out of the Shadowlands somehow.\nAlternatively, they may have been created by the aforementioned &lt;a href=\"Hir%27eek\"&gt;Hir'eek&lt;/a&gt; in the same way that other &lt;a href=\"Wild%20God\"&gt;Wild God&lt;/a&gt;s created humanoid animal races."}
